preface
Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.
One focus of the work of the Court of Auditors should therefore be on the examination of this area.
This is especially true for VAT fraud.
This alone results in tax losses estimated at 100 billion Euro1 a year in the European Union.
Already at the VI EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, the participants pointed out the need for increased cooperation.
This allows the auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimise the audit practice.
VAT (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, the Court of Auditors of both countries audited for the first time in parallel in the area of the United States.
The relevant audit report was published in 2008.
Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Court of Auditors is needed. This allows it to be fully assessed whether the measures taken are capable of effectively addressing the VAT fraud.
The two Court of Auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany report on the control check
