2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit
The Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed a check on the administration of the VAT.
In the previous parallel audit, they had uncovered suspected cases of intra-Community turnover,
Which made a reconsider appear fit for purpose.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two Court of Auditors made recommendations on the administration of the VAT.
The aim of the review was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases identified should be investigated.
The audit also looked at other issues. These included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community turnover, mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and VAT auditing for large companies.
In doing so, the Court of Auditors found:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit
• Recommendation 1: The rules on the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
In the first audit, the Court of Auditors compared the registration procedures for the VAT in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the expansion of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of VAT lilichs.
The draft also provided for common arrangements for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.
The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate arrangements in accordance with their decision in principle to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.
The final version of the draft was reached by political agreement on the final version of the draft.
These common rules are no longer included. The two Court of Auditors regret this.
They still consider such regulations important in order to combat VAT fraud in a preventative way.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports As a result of the initial audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to Member States that the summary reports (ZM) be submitted on a monthly basis in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community turnover could then be reviewed in a timely manner.
Council Directive 2008/117/EG on amending Directive 2006/112/EG on the common VAT system for combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the levy of the ZM to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation did not enter into force until 1 July 2010. In doing so, it has not transposed the obligation to grant ZM a monthly levy into national law on time.
• Recommendation 3: Data matching of VAT pre-registrations and ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to review the amalgamation of procedures for VAT pre-registrations and ZM The German financial administration has approved the Federal Audit Office Recommendation taken up and a working group set up to develop possible solutions.
The work is still ongoing.
The Federal Audit Office will monitor further developments.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level In the course of the initial audit, the two Court of Auditors agreed that an effective risk management system would not be provided by one Member State alone. Can be developed.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches to a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
Failure to do so will focus fraudsters on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems that have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU-EUROCANET, while the Federal Audit Office focused on German participation in the "Risk Management Platform."
2. Review of selected intra-Community sales
During the first audit, the Court of Auditors had jointly examined transactions which were doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or whether they had actually been carried out or that were different from the taxpayers of the two countries in the VAT pre-registrations (or VAT statements) or ZM. had been explained.
The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.
The audits by the tax offices (FIS) of both countries had not yet ended at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.
The inspection has shown that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective financial administrations had taken appropriate measures to do so (including subsequent VAT refunds or preventing pre-tax refunds).
3. Review of selected, particularly risky intra-Community sales
The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between EU taxpayers covered by the EUROCANET system.
EUROCANET is used to identify risky taxpayers.
Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
This did not provide information on which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.
The NKU found normal transactions in selected transactions as well as those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud.
The FIS were only able to check high-risk sales to a limited extent. This was particularly true of so-called "missing traders," whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
It is advisable that customs and tax authorities work more closely together to track the likelihood of goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the end customer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to take an active part in EUROCANET because, from their point of view, there is no sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Audit Office found that the German financial administration uses other tools to identify risk-taking taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
Created by EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should feed into the planned network for combating VAT fraud.
4.Mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of receivables
Interstate administrative assistance in recovering claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental administrative assistance in the recovery of receivables in the CZ and Germany are dealt with in the same way.
Federal Audit Office and NKU compared the statistics forwarded to the European Commission by both Member States for the years 2006 to 2008.
Those statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two Court of Auditors consider it useful to revisit the statistics at EU level in order to avoid any remaining discrepancies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should include more information about the VAT.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both Court of Auditors believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should support Member States in this if this is desired.
5. VAT test at large companies
The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to the VAT audit of large companies in both countries.
In addition, they collected information from the financial administrations with a questionnaire that they considered important in this context.
It became clear that the situation in both countries is different.
The CZ has a system for selecting risky cases that involves a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts).
As a result, the VAT control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.
A special financial office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.
There is no similar system in Germany yet. This makes it difficult to control and analyze USt control as a whole.
The German financial administration is concentrating more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the VAT pre-registrations or VAT declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components that are still to be improved support the evaluation of this data.
