4. Review of the management of VAT in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint review
4.1.1 implementation of recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for the registration of taxpayers within the EU supported
In response to the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be adjusted and that new rules for the cancellation of registration in the CZ be introduced.
These amended rules should more effectively curb the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the FIS did not delete the VAT registration of taxpayers if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech Law No. 235/2004 (referred to below as the "VAT Act").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to oblige the FIS to delete them if taxpayers repeatedly do not file VAT declarations.
Under the Czech VAT Act, the FA may delete the registration of a taxpayer on its own initiative if (a) the taxpayer has not made any transactions for 12 consecutive months and the FA has not informed of the reasons for doing so; (b) the taxpayer has not fulfilled his duties under the VAT Act; (c) the taxpayer no longer meets the requirements for the tax liability.
The first audit had shown that, as a result of the existing legal situation, FA Prague 1 must delete the VAT registration of "foreign taxpayer members 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year, if they do not apply in the current calendar year and Payment from VAT were obligated.
The FA Prague 1 often did not delete the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant determination of the time limit could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2009.
Accordingly, the FA has the power to delete the registration of a foreign taxpayer if he has not provided taxable or tax-exempt goods deliveries or services entitled to deduction in the previous calendar year.
Recommendation 2
Monthly levy of the ZM
As a result of the initial audit, the Court of Auditors had recommended that the monthly levy of ZM be introduced.
The Council Directive, which shortened the turnaround for the levy of the ZM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be surrendered if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) of the VAT Act are provided to a person registered in a Member State other than those subject to VAT.
The prerequisite is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services. This obligation is the result of Directive 2008/8/EG of the Council amending Directive 2006/112/EG on the location of the service.
Recommendation 3
Matchery of the data of the VAT pre-registrations and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data. This recommendation related to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically compares the data on intra-Community transactions from the VAT declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Replacing successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of the VAT is an indispensable prerequisite for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.
That is why the fight against VAT fraud is of paramount interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is demonstrated, among other things, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In it, an external expert estimated the VAT failure for the 25 Member States between 2000 and 2006. After evaluating the available data, the tax shortfall for the period referred to was estimated at between EUR 90 billion and EUR 113 billion. This was based on the fact that the EU-25 lose an average of 12% of the sales taxes they are entitled to each year.
The estimated estimated tax shortfall for the CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that a Member State alone could not develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches to an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
For this purpose, intra-Community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in EUROCANET were selected (see Chapter 4.3).
The EUROFISC network aims to optimise administrative assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively. Cooperation between the competent authorities should be improved in order to identify cases of fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential of intra-Community sales.
The ECOFIN-Rat6 endorsed EUROFISC on 7 October 2008, while at the same time adopting the principles for the functioning of the system.
EUROCANET, developed by the Belgian Financial Administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, serves as a model for EUROFISC.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky sales and identify entrepreneurs involved in the organised VAT scam.
