Since the German financial administration did not participate in the exchange of data via EUROCANET, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with a German VAT identification number were classified as risk-prone by the German financial administration.
The audit identified both normal transactions and those suspected of carousel fraud or other VAT fraud.
In the cases in question, the FIS exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003,
For example:
• FIS found no suspicion of risky sales when examining early warning information.
The taxpayers concerned were constantly monitored because their data was stored in EUROCANET.
• In the review of risk-prone transactions, FIS was unable to prove breaches of the rules for calculating the tax base and the VAT on the basis of the accounting documents submitted, even though they have not been incontested in the case of transport and Storing the goods or revealing business relationships with letterbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers did not cooperate with the FIS and could not be contacted.
The relevant FIS reviewed most of the risky taxpayers and transactions mentioned in EUROCANET early warning reports.
However, their ability to review risky sales, especially so-called "missing traders," are limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly provide proof of fraudulent action by the taxpayer.
